On September 30, 1928, that is exactly 90 years ago, the British bacteriologist Alexander Fleming announced an unprecedented discovery.
The discovery of penicillin marked the beginning of the era of modern antibiotics, brought Fleming worldwide fame and made him a Nobel laureate.
By the way, the isolation of penicillin from fungi was not Fleming&#39;s first discovery.
A few years earlier, when he had a cold, he sowed mucus from his own nose on a Petri dish (this is such a glass lid in which experiments are carried out with bacteria) and after a few days found that the bacteria there were destroyed.
Almost as accidentally, he discovered penicillin.
Fleming&#39;s name was included in the list of 100 most prominent personalities in the history of mankind.
His discovery, according to many scientists, changed the course of history.
With the help of penicillin, medicine began to cope with most of the most ancient diseases that were previously considered incurable - tuberculosis, syphilis, gangrene ...
When, shortly after receiving the Nobel Prize, in 1945, Fleming arrived in the French capital, the Parisian newspapers wrote: &quot;To defeat fascism and liberate France, he did more than dozens of divisions.&quot;
According to experts, Fleming&#39;s discovery of the world&#39;s first antibiotic saved the lives of more than 200 million people on Earth.
Alexander Fleming died at his home in London in 1955 of a heart attack.
He was cremated and a week later his ashes were buried in London&#39;s famous St. Paul&#39;s Cathedral.
Where, by the way, my wife and I paid attention to this talkative Russian-speaking guide.
