AfD became the second most popular in Germany
The anti-immigrant &quot;Alternative for Germany&quot; beats another record of popularity, and the ratings of Angela Merkel are falling.
Apparently, the people of Germany began to seriously tire of Angela Merkel&#39;s immigration policy, thanks to which the country has become a coveted target for millions of refugees from the Middle East.
The latest opinion polls show this most clearly, according to which the anti-immigrant party Alternative for Germany is becoming more popular, and the positions of the ruling bloc Merkel and Seehofer are weakening.
This week, the AfD broke another record, rising to second place in the rating of people&#39;s sympathies.
Right-wing conservatives, with 17 percent of their popularity, managed to beat the Social Democrats, who have about 16 percent.
The gap of one percentage point can be attributed to a statistical error, but one cannot but note the established fact that the AfD, created in 2013 from a small group of eurosceptic economists, managed to turn into a serious political force.
Leadership in the overall standings is still held by the ruling block of the CSU / CDU, which has about 30 percent.
However, there is a tendency to lose points here - back in April, support for Angela Merkel&#39;s bloc was four percentage points higher.
