By tracking the distribution of dark matter and dark energy, which account for more than 95 percent of the energy-mass of the observable world, scientists, working within the standard ΛCDM (Λ Cold Dark Matter) cosmological model, estimated the rate of expansion of the Universe, which turned out to be slightly slower than previously thought.
